Interaction Design

# 

<span key="cf508c1b4b5947949bba3f5b7c6377a5"><span offset-key="cf508c1b4b5947949bba3f5b7c6377a5:0">Interaction Design</span></span>

<span key="e0098dd6f19e4dcf89c74c16288d051b">**Interaction design**<span offset-key="e0098dd6f19e4dcf89c74c16288d051b:1"> (IxD) is another subset of UX that focuses on </span>**the junction between the user and the product.**</span>

<span key="679decf310b64bf38a19b380581bdcab"><span offset-key="679decf310b64bf38a19b380581bdcab:0">IxD tries to answer questions like:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="b793927902084924a4c943485b72c258"><span offset-key="b793927902084924a4c943485b72c258:0">How is a user inclined to interact with a product under certain circumstances?</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="63fa0da60f1c4eafba20cfc9224b22b0"><span offset-key="63fa0da60f1c4eafba20cfc9224b22b0:0">How do we </span>*want*<span offset-key="63fa0da60f1c4eafba20cfc9224b22b0:2"> our users to interact with a particular product?</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="4674d6f5d86845f58925288538795228"><span offset-key="4674d6f5d86845f58925288538795228:0">How do we drive user interactions to achieve product goals?</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="04b3de34b639427dac7b0d66b383eb84"><span offset-key="04b3de34b639427dac7b0d66b383eb84:0">How can we build something that lets users accomplish their goals in an optimal way?</span></span>

## 

<span key="25973aea2566419ba66c2e8a51ff91b2"><span offset-key="25973aea2566419ba66c2e8a51ff91b2:0">The Five Dimensions Framework of Interaction Design</span></span>

<span key="3ae6e0a0132c4a5baf7cb5b2899ce0b8"><span offset-key="3ae6e0a0132c4a5baf7cb5b2899ce0b8:0">In 2007, </span></span><a href="https://www.uxmatters.com/mt/archives/2007/07/what-puts-the-design-in-interaction-design.php" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="13d35f643a20478398722688f4b7d518" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-7019_259-7020-237__"><span data-key="01f27d4c58694a5ca7a92d174d5e27e0"><span data-offset-key="01f27d4c58694a5ca7a92d174d5e27e0:0">Kevin Silver (Links to an external site.)</span></span></span></a><span key="2073bdf305114c5cbe840815c5640924"><span offset-key="2073bdf305114c5cbe840815c5640924:0"> adapted </span></span><a href="http://feiramoderna.net/download/pos-positivo/MOGGRIDGE-Bill/DesigningInteractions_00_foreword.pdf" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="e8e9f4a715d84311a46266a569985fac" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-7019_259-7020-237__"><span data-key="7079fc8689204099bda7af17af0e59f6"><span data-offset-key="7079fc8689204099bda7af17af0e59f6:0">Gillian Crampton Smith's (Links to an external site.)</span></span></span></a><span key="0e8d60c0eb4d45d99b0b6a7297b3a9cd"><span offset-key="0e8d60c0eb4d45d99b0b6a7297b3a9cd:0"> four "dimensions" of interaction design "languages" to add a fifth dimension, giving rise to the "Five Dimensions" framework:</span></span>

Dimension #

Dimension

Definition

<span key="c37768cb33944c778e942d8cdc7cf363"><span offset-key="c37768cb33944c778e942d8cdc7cf363:0">1-D</span></span>

<span key="6797c19546814c37af6deda75c66c5df"><span offset-key="6797c19546814c37af6deda75c66c5df:0">Words</span></span>

<span key="d7368c2900664115862ebed69faee1de"><span offset-key="d7368c2900664115862ebed69faee1de:0">Words are themselves interactions, and should be used with care.</span></span>

<span key="94060afe753c4e8fb4ee32383425892a"><span offset-key="94060afe753c4e8fb4ee32383425892a:0">2-D</span></span>

<span key="4d75788d0f614bfda82203fa3921e42d"><span offset-key="4d75788d0f614bfda82203fa3921e42d:0">Visual Representations</span></span>

<span key="d15768015eb049d6b83b8b0acad28390"><span offset-key="d15768015eb049d6b83b8b0acad28390:0">Typography, diagrams, icons, and other graphics with which users interact.</span></span>

<span key="cbaa4379a820406fb826dd2cc362e58e"><span offset-key="cbaa4379a820406fb826dd2cc362e58e:0">3-D</span></span>

<span key="21e736c5a71d495eb215558b4bdfa89e"><span offset-key="21e736c5a71d495eb215558b4bdfa89e:0">Physical Objects or Space</span></span>

<span key="f6655a9a48c84dec93ea593effea4eca"><span offset-key="f6655a9a48c84dec93ea593effea4eca:0">Objects with which or spaces within which users interact in the "real world".</span></span>

<span key="72d93fedaf1b4b17855b4fd6615a7bb8"><span offset-key="72d93fedaf1b4b17855b4fd6615a7bb8:0">4-D</span></span>

<span key="70817c4817074071983087104fc68d14"><span offset-key="70817c4817074071983087104fc68d14:0">Time</span></span>

<span key="e19c22f64f8b438fa723de3b49fd0ca6"><span offset-key="e19c22f64f8b438fa723de3b49fd0ca6:0">The time within which users interact (with content that changes over time).</span></span>

<span key="5514ce50f4664defac2452705403ec5d"><span offset-key="5514ce50f4664defac2452705403ec5d:0">5-D</span></span>

<span key="a37fd2609e2742ef9aa8c868be03c4cc"><span offset-key="a37fd2609e2742ef9aa8c868be03c4cc:0">Behavior</span></span>

<span key="a6276f9d3bb64e2e9e261aaf3b506f4d"><span offset-key="a6276f9d3bb64e2e9e261aaf3b506f4d:0">Action and reaction, including how users interact with the product.</span></span>

<span key="c270aae0e2f8451fbeedc219fdd900e5"><span offset-key="c270aae0e2f8451fbeedc219fdd900e5:0">These dimensions define different ways that users can interact with a productâ€”often all at once. They might be helpful to consider as your build a product, because they'll force you to be conscious of the fact that users will constantly have an impression along each dimension.</span></span>
